I don&#x27;t understand why the lazy algorithms aren&#x27;t enough. Can&#x27;t we have an assignment to vectors from lazy streams, or constructors from them?<p>Why can&#x27;t the<p><pre><code>    std::vector<int> ints =
        read_ints() | cont::sort | cont::unique;
</code></pre>
from TFA can&#x27;t be done &quot;as lazily as possible&quot; (i.e., sort eagerly and uniq lazily). Alternatively, something like<p><pre><code>    std::vector<int> ints(read_ints() | cont::sort | cont::unique);
</code></pre>
or even<p><pre><code>    std::vector<int> ints;
    read_ints() | cont::sort | cont::unique > ints;
</code></pre>
What reason could we have for making `read_ints` and `unique` eager by default?<p>Performance-wise, the lazy filter works in constant space, will result in fewer dcache misses if the data set is large, and (I <i>think</i>) provides more opportunity for the optimizer to do clever things. The eager chain may have better icache performance if the filter is very complicated.<p>And it&#x27;s easy to go from lazy to eager -- just put everything in a vector. If you want to go from eager to lazy, though, you&#x27;re out of luck.

